2.1 Data Preparation Deliverables

Introduction

The purpose of the data preparation stage was to transform the raw customer churn dataset into a clean, structured, and machine-readable format suitable for later analysis and modeling. Data preparation is essential because raw datasets are often not ready for direct use in clustering or machine learning. Even when a dataset appears complete, it still needs to be inspected, standardized, encoded, and formatted correctly so that later steps are reliable and reproducible.
In this project, the raw dataset was loaded from `data/raw/Dataset_ATS_v2.csv` and preserved unchanged. This was done to ensure that the original data source remained intact for traceability and future reference. All preprocessing work was performed on copies of the dataset, and the resulting outputs were saved separately in the processed data folder.
The main tasks completed in this stage were:
ΓÇó	inspection of the raw dataset
ΓÇó	preprocessing and cleaning
ΓÇó	conversion of categorical variables into numeric form
ΓÇó	splitting into training and testing datasets
ΓÇó	application of scaling techniques to selected features

1. Initial Data Inspection
Before applying any transformation, the raw dataset was explored to understand its structure and quality. This included checking:
ΓÇó	the number of rows and columns
ΓÇó	column names
ΓÇó	data types
ΓÇó	missing values
ΓÇó	duplicate rows
ΓÇó	unique values in categorical columns
ΓÇó	summary statistics for numerical columns
The dataset contained 7043 rows and 10 columns. The original columns were:
ΓÇó	`gender`
ΓÇó	`SeniorCitizen`
ΓÇó	`Dependents`
ΓÇó	`tenure`
ΓÇó	`PhoneService`
ΓÇó	`MultipleLines`
ΓÇó	`InternetService`
ΓÇó	`Contract`
ΓÇó	`MonthlyCharges`
ΓÇó	`Churn`
This inspection step was important because preprocessing decisions should be based on observed characteristics of the dataset rather than assumptions.

Why this was used
Initial inspection was used to understand the datasetΓÇÖs current condition and decide what preparation steps were necessary.


Why it was important
Without this step, later cleaning or transformation could be inaccurate or unnecessary. For example, applying missing-value imputation without first checking whether missing values exist would be poor practice.

2. Missing Value Check
A missing-value check was conducted across all columns using pandas.

Result
No missing values were found in the dataset.

Why this was used
Missing values can cause errors or distortions in machine learning algorithms and clustering models. A missing-value check is therefore a standard part of preprocessing.

Why this choice was important
Even though no missing values were found, this step was still necessary because it confirmed that no imputation method was required. This prevented unnecessary or artificial modification of the dataset.

Decision made
Since no missing values were present, no imputation or deletion strategy was applied.

3. Duplicate Row Check
A duplicate-row check was also performed.

Result
The dataset contained 302 duplicate rows.

Why this was used
Duplicate rows can bias model learning and pattern detection, especially if they represent accidental repeated records rather than genuine repeated cases.

Why the duplicates were not removed
The dataset did not include a unique customer identifier such as a customer ID. Because of this, it could not be confirmed whether duplicate rows represented:
ΓÇó	accidental duplicate records, or
ΓÇó	different customers with the same recorded attributes
Removing them automatically would therefore have been an unsupported assumption.

Decision made
The duplicates were documented but retained.

Why this choice was important
This was the safest and most defensible option. It preserved data integrity and avoided deleting potentially valid observations without evidence.

4. Column Name Standardisation
The column names were standardized by:
ΓÇó	removing extra spaces
ΓÇó	converting all text to lowercase
ΓÇó	replacing spaces with underscores
ΓÇó	removing special characters where necessary
For example:
ΓÇó	`SeniorCitizen` became `seniorcitizen`
ΓÇó	`MonthlyCharges` became `monthlycharges`

Why this was used
Standardized column names make the dataset easier to work with in Python scripts and notebooks.

Why this choice was important
This improves readability, reduces coding errors, and ensures consistency across different files and team membersΓÇÖ work. It also makes the data pipeline easier to reproduce.

5. Standardisation of Categorical Text Values
All categorical text values were standardized by:
ΓÇó	removing unnecessary spaces
ΓÇó	converting values to lowercase
For example:
ΓÇó	`Yes` became `yes`
ΓÇó	`No` became `no`
ΓÇó	`Male` became `male`
ΓÇó	`Female` became `female`

Why this was used
Text categories often appear consistent but may contain subtle differences in case or spacing. If these are not cleaned, the encoding stage can treat them as separate categories incorrectly.

Why this choice was important
This step ensured consistent category labels and prevented errors during encoding. It also improved the reliability of downstream analysis.

6. Identification of Numeric and Categorical Features
After cleaning the structure and text values, the variables were separated into numeric and categorical types.
Numeric features identified
ΓÇó	`seniorcitizen`
ΓÇó	`tenure`
ΓÇó	`monthlycharges`
Categorical features identified
ΓÇó	`gender`
ΓÇó	`dependents`
ΓÇó	`phoneservice`
ΓÇó	`multiplelines`
ΓÇó	`internetservice`
