Why this was used
Different preprocessing methods are required for different variable types. Numeric variables may need scaling, while categorical variables must be encoded.

Why this choice was important
Correct feature identification is essential to choosing appropriate preprocessing techniques and avoiding incorrect transformations.

7. Preprocessed Dataset
The next step was to prepare a preprocessed dataset that addressed categorical encoding and target preparation.
Target variable conversion
The target variable `churn` originally contained text values:
ΓÇó	`yes`
ΓÇó	`no`
It was converted into numeric form:
ΓÇó	`no` = 0
ΓÇó	`yes` = 1

Why this was used
Machine learning models require the target variable to be numeric rather than text.

Why this choice was important
This binary conversion preserved the meaning of the target while making it usable in later modeling and evaluation.

8. Encoding of Categorical Variables
The categorical input features were converted into numeric form using one-hot encoding with:
`pd.get_dummies(..., drop_first=True)`
The encoded categorical variables were:
ΓÇó	`gender`
ΓÇó	`dependents`
ΓÇó	`phoneservice`
ΓÇó	`multiplelines`
ΓÇó	`internetservice`
ΓÇó	`contract`

Why one-hot encoding was used
One-hot encoding was chosen because the categorical variables in this dataset are nominal or binary. This method converts each category into a separate numeric column without imposing an artificial order.

Why this choice was important
Alternative approaches such as label encoding could incorrectly suggest a numeric ranking between categories, which would be misleading. One-hot encoding is more appropriate because it preserves category meaning without creating false numerical relationships.

Why `drop_first=True` was used
This option removes one reference category from each encoded feature to avoid unnecessary redundancy in the dataset. It also keeps the dataset more compact.

9. Boolean-to-Integer Conversion
After one-hot encoding, some resulting dummy columns were stored as boolean values (`True` and `False`). These were converted into integers (`1` and `0`).

Why this was used
Although boolean values can technically be used in some contexts, converting them to integers creates a fully numeric dataset that is easier to store, inspect, and reuse.

Why this choice was important
This step improved consistency across all columns and made the dataset more suitable for modeling and export.

