11. Training and Testing Sets
After preprocessing, the dataset was split into training and testing sets.

Method used
An 80:20 split was applied using `train_test_split()` from scikit-learn, with stratification based on the `churn` target variable.
Result
ΓÇó	training set size: 5634 rows
ΓÇó	testing set size: 1409 rows

Why this was used
The purpose of train-test splitting is to allow future models to be trained on one portion of the data and evaluated on another unseen portion. This helps measure whether a model generalizes well instead of simply memorizing the data.

Why stratification was used
The churn variable is imbalanced, with more non-churn customers than churn customers. Stratified sampling preserves this class balance in both the training and testing sets.

Why this choice was important
Without stratification, the class distribution in train and test could differ too much, making later evaluation unreliable.

Output files created
ΓÇó	`data/processed/churn_train.csv`
ΓÇó	`data/processed/churn_test.csv`

12. Scaling Techniques
After splitting, scaling was applied to the continuous numeric features.
Scaling technique used
`StandardScaler` from scikit-learn
Features scaled
ΓÇó	`tenure`
ΓÇó	`monthlycharges`
Features not scaled
ΓÇó	binary variables such as:
  - `gender_male`
  - `dependents_yes`
  - `phoneservice_yes`
  - `multiplelines_yes`
  - `internetservice_fiber optic`
  - `contract_one year`
  - `contract_two year`
ΓÇó	`seniorcitizen`, because it is also binary

Why StandardScaler was used
`StandardScaler` transforms the selected features so that they have:
ΓÇó	mean close to 0
ΓÇó	standard deviation close to 1

Why this was used
Scaling is important because some algorithms, especially clustering methods and neural networks, are sensitive to differences in feature magnitude. Without scaling, variables with larger numeric ranges can dominate the model.

Why only selected features were scaled
`tenure` and `monthlycharges` are continuous features with wider ranges, while the other encoded variables are binary 0/1 variables. Scaling only the continuous features is a practical and interpretable approach.

Why this choice was important
This prevents larger-scale features from overpowering other inputs while preserving the meaning of binary variables.

Why the scaler was fitted on the training set only
The scaler was fitted only on the training data and then applied to the test data.
This was done to avoid data leakage, where information from the test set unintentionally influences the training process.

Why this choice was important
Avoiding data leakage is essential for valid future model evaluation.
Output files created
ΓÇó	`data/processed/churn_train_scaled.csv`
ΓÇó	`data/processed/churn_test_scaled.csv`

