14. Why These Choices Were Appropriate
The preprocessing choices made in this project were appropriate because they were based on the actual characteristics of the dataset.
ΓÇó	Missing-value handling was not applied because no missing values were present.
ΓÇó	Duplicate rows were retained because there was no customer ID to justify automatic removal.
ΓÇó	One-hot encoding was used because the dataset contained nominal categorical variables.
ΓÇó	Train-test split was stratified because the churn classes were imbalanced.
ΓÇó	`StandardScaler` was applied to continuous variables because those features had larger numeric ranges and would likely affect clustering and later modeling if left unscaled.
Together, these decisions produced a dataset that is more reliable, more consistent, and more suitable for further analysis.

15. Conclusion
The data preparation stage successfully converted the raw churn dataset into a structured and machine-readable format suitable for the next project steps. The dataset was explored, cleaned, standardized, encoded, split into training and testing sets, and selectively scaled using an appropriate technique.
These deliverables now provide a strong foundation for clustering analysis and later predictive modeling. The choices made during preprocessing were not arbitrary; each one was applied because it matched the nature of the data and improved the quality and usability of the final outputs.
